I don&#x27;t know if ActiveRecord is capable of doing this, but here is how to do it with Django ORM:<p>in models.py:<p><pre><code>    class Node(models.Model):
        parent = models.ForeignKey(&#x27;self&#x27;, related_name=&#x27;children&#x27;)

</code></pre>
in the view:<p><pre><code>    nodes = Node.objects.prefetch_related(&#x27;children&#x27;)

</code></pre>
in template:<p><pre><code>    {% for node in nodes %}
        {% for subnode in node.children.all %}
        ...
        {% endfor %}
    {% endfor %}

</code></pre>
This will make exactly two queries; one for all the parent nodes, and one for the children nodes. Django will make the pairing automagically, so you don&#x27;t have to do it in view code.
